first statement, the implication is not true anymore!", "In a probabilistic setting, Xi's are random variables, and \u201con average increase\u201d is equivalent to a positive correlation. Consider a simple exemplar setting and assume that the correlation between X\u2081 and X\u2082 and the correlation between X\u2081 and X\u2083 are the same and equal to 0.5. To have an intuition, a famous example of two random variables with a correlation almost equal to 0.5 is the height of a father and the height of his son\u00b9.", "For our simple exemplar setting, there are three possible scenarios:", "Basic conclusion: probabilistic settings are against our intuition! However, now one should ask whether there is any information in the statement \u201cthere are positive correlations between X\u2081 and X\u2082, and X\u2081 and X\u2083\u201d about the correlation between X\u2082 and X\u2083.", "To find the additional information, we have to do some more formal analysis. To do so, let us consider the correlation matrix", "Then, the formal statement of our question is: Can we find a bound for the value of \u03c3\u2082\u2083 given the values of \u03c3\u2081\u2082 and \u03c3\u2081\u2083? The answer is yes!", "As a correlation matrix, \u03a3 needs to be positive semi-definite. Exploiting this condition, one can find the following (relatively weak) bounds\u00b2 for the value of \u03c3\u2082\u2083:", "The simple but interesting conclusion is that as long as we have (|\u03c3\u2081\u2082|+|\u03c3\u2081\u2083|)\u00b2>2, we can at least be sure about the sign of \u03c3\u2082\u2083; obviously it was not the case for our exemplar setting.", "We can go further and find, for each pair of \u03c3\u2081\u2082 and \u03c3\u2081\u2083, the minimum and the maximum values of \u03c3\u2082\u2083 for which \u03a3 remains positive semi-definite. These values are shown as heatmaps in Fig. 4. The right plot shows the bounds for the case that \u03c3\u2081\u2083 is fixed and equal to 0.5, which corresponds to the dashed lines on the heatmaps. The three different scenarios in the 1st part are shown by three circles lying between the upper and the lower bounds.", "A quick and simple conclusion can be: Except for the extreme cases (the ones close to the corners in the heatmaps), we cannot say much about \u03c3\u2082\u2083 given \u03c3\u2081\u2082 and \u03c3\u2081\u2083.", "The code (in Julia language) for the analyses can be found here.", "\u00b9 See here for a reference.", "\u00b2 The derivation of the bounds remains as an exercise for interested readers.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "CS PhD student in the Laboratory of Computational Neuroscience at EPFL || Personal website: https://sites.google.com/view/modirsha"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F147bd1164887&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fa-misinterpretation-of-correlations-147bd1164887&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fa-misinterpretation-of-correlations-147bd1164887&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------